ce:section.ce:para:
The photocatalytic active sites, e.g., carbonyl groups [38], were found in N/S-CDs. Thus methylene blue and methyl violet were employed to estimate the visible-light photocatalytic activities of N/S-CDs. Using commercial un-doped CDs and the first-order degradation rate constant for the comparison of photocatalytic activity, the degradation rate of N/S-CDs was much higher (beyond two times) than that of CDs (Fig. 7
                        ). The difference of photocatalytic activity might be due to the difference of main surface groups on N/S-CDs (including hydroxyl, carbonyl) and CDs (including mainly amino and hydroxyl, Fig. 8
                        ). Therefore, we speculate that surface carbonyl groups on N/S-CDs were its photocatalytic active site, which was consistent with the results reported by Hu's group [38]. The surface carbonyl groups facilitated the charge separation and transfer in N/S-CDs. Therefore, N/S-CDs generated strongly oxidizing holes on the reaction surface under light irradiation.
